<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - ROCKWELL TANDEM AXLE FORWARD REAR DRIVE UNITS - ASSEMBLE
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>ASSEMBLE</title>
        <svcsubsecinfo>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To prevent serious eye injury, always wear safe eye protection when doing maintenance or
                        service.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>If the original ring gear and drive pinion are being installed, go to
                        <hotlnk document="s14011_33.xml" xrefid="x1401105">Drive Pinion Assembly</hotlnk>.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>If a new ring gear and drive pinion are installed, the correct thickness of the shim pack
                        between the inner bearing cup and the carrier must be determined. Refer to the following
                        procedure.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </svcsubsecinfo>
        <svcproc id="x1401107" svcproctype="assemble" graphiccount="3">
            <title>DETERMINING THE THICKNESS OF THE SHIM PACK FOR A NEW DRIVE PINION (DEPTH OF PINION)</title>
            <para>Refer to
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401171">Figure 71</hotlnk>.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401171" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg14/g1401171.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         resolution="150"/>
                <caption>Figure 71. Determining Thickness of Shim Pack</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. SPACER</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. HELICAL DRIVEN GEAR</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. OUTER BEARING CONE</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. OUTER BEARING CUP</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. SPACER</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. SHIMS</callout1>
                    <callout1>7. INNER BEARING CONE</callout1>
                    <callout1>8. DRIVE PINION</callout1>
                    <callout1>9. INNER BEARING CUP</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Use this procedure if a new drive pinion or ring gear set is installed or if the depth of the
                        original drive pinion has to be adjusted.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a micrometer to measure the thickness of the shim pack that was removed from the
                    differential carrier. Record the measurement for later use (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1401172">Figure 72</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1401172" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg14/g1401172.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             resolution="150"/>
                    <caption>Figure 72. Measure Thickness of Shim Pack</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Look at the pinion cone (PC) variation number on the drive pinion that is being
                    replaced. Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s14011_29.xml" xrefid="x1401106">Gear Set Information, step 4</hotlnk>
                    for examples and location of the number. Record the number for later use (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1401173">Figure 73</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1401173" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg14/g1401173.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             resolution="150"/>
                    <caption>Figure 73. Record Pinion Cone Variation Number</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The pinion cone number can be either 1,000ths of an inch (0.000 inch), PC+3, PC-3, +3 or -3
                        equals 0.003 inch (.076 mm).
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>To change millimeters to inches, multiply millimeters by 0.039. To change inches to
                        millimeters, multiply inches by 25.40.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the old pinion cone number is a plus (+), add the cone number to the thickness of the
                    old shim pack that was measured in step 1.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the old pinion cone number is a minus (-), subtract the cone number from the
                    thickness of the old shim pack that was measured in step 1.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Look at the pinion cone (PC) variation number on the new drive pinion that will be
                    installed. Record the number for later use.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the new pinion cone number is a plus (+), subtract the number from the standard shim
                    pack thickness that was calculated in step 3 or 4. Make a shim pack of new shims to the determined
                    thickness. For an example, refer to Table 2 below.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the new pinion cone number is a minus (-), add the number to the standard shim pack
                    thickness that was calculated in step 3 or 4. Make a shim pack of new shims to the determined
                    thickness. For an example, refer to Table 2 below.
                </para>
            </step1>
